        <div class="verdict">⭐ Rating: 4.0/5 — Solid mid-market platform with strong estimating</div>

        <p>Construction Online (formerly ConstructionSuite, now branded as UDA ConstructionOnline) is a long-standing platform that's built a loyal following among residential and light commercial contractors. It's not as well-known as Buildertrend or Procore, but among contractors who use it, satisfaction tends to be high — particularly for estimating and specification writing.</p>

        <h2>What is UDA ConstructionOnline?</h2>
        <p>UDA Technologies has been building construction software since 1995. ConstructionOnline is their cloud-based platform combining project management, estimating, scheduling, client communication, and financial tracking in one system. It's aimed squarely at small to mid-market contractors who want more sophistication than basic tools but don't need (or want to pay for) Procore-level enterprise features.</p>

        <h2>Pricing</h2>
        <p>UDA ConstructionOnline is subscription-based with pricing that varies based on company size and selected features. Entry-level packages start in the range of $200–400/month, with more comprehensive plans for larger teams ranging higher. UDA offers custom quotes — contact them directly for current pricing as it's not always published publicly.</p>

        <p>Importantly, UDA offers unlimited projects across all plans — you're not paying per project, which matters for contractors running many concurrent jobs.</p>

        <h2>Core features</h2>

        <h3>Estimating — A genuine strength</h3>
        <p>UDA's estimating module is considered one of its strongest features. It includes a pre-built library of construction cost items, division-based estimate organization (CSI format), and the ability to build complex estimates with assemblies. The ability to generate polished client proposals directly from estimates is a standout feature.</p>

        <ul>
          <li>Pre-built cost library with thousands of line items</li>
          <li>Assembly-based estimating for repetitive components</li>
          <li>Proposal generation directly from estimate data</li>
          <li>Integration with RSMeans cost data (optional)</li>
          <li>Estimate-to-budget conversion for job cost tracking</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Project scheduling</h3>
        <p>ConstructionOnline includes a Gantt-based scheduling system with task dependencies, critical path identification, and schedule templates you can reuse across similar project types. It's not quite as slick as Buildertrend's scheduling interface, but it's functional and complete.</p>

        <h3>Client portal</h3>
        <p>The client portal allows homeowners to review selections, approve change orders, view project progress, and communicate with the team. It's comparable to what Buildertrend offers, though Buildertrend's client portal is generally considered more polished.</p>

        <h3>Specifications</h3>
        <p>One differentiator: UDA has strong specification writing tools, making it popular among contractors who need to produce detailed project specifications as part of their contract documentation. This is more important in commercial and design-build work than in straightforward residential construction.</p>

        <h3>Financials and job costing</h3>
        <p>ConstructionOnline tracks budgets, purchase orders, change orders, and invoices. It integrates with QuickBooks for full accounting. The job costing isn't as real-time or visual as JobTread's, but it covers what most mid-market contractors need.</p>

        <h2>Pros</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Comprehensive platform — estimating through project completion in one system</li>
          <li>Strong estimating module, particularly for specification-heavy projects</li>
          <li>Unlimited projects included</li>
          <li>Long-established platform with a stable development track record</li>
          <li>Good customer support reputation among existing users</li>
          <li>Windows desktop application available for contractors who prefer local software</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Cons</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Less well-known than Buildertrend — fewer trained staff and less community support</li>
          <li>UI feels less modern than newer competitors</li>
          <li>Mobile app less capable than Buildertrend or Procore</li>
          <li>Pricing not always transparent without contacting sales</li>
          <li>Smaller integration ecosystem than the market leaders</li>
          <li>Less suitable for pure commercial work compared to Procore</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Who ConstructionOnline is best for</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Custom homebuilders and remodelers who need serious estimating capabilities</li>
          <li>Design-build contractors who produce detailed specifications</li>
          <li>Contractors who've outgrown spreadsheets but find Buildertrend's pricing prohibitive</li>
          <li>Teams that want a Windows desktop option alongside cloud access</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>How it compares to Buildertrend</h2>
